  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Women Farmers in Vegetable Value Chain</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="4">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">- Construct 1 Low land well based micro lift irrigation for covering 50 farmers. 

- Construct 100 Water harvesting / Seepage tanks to cover 600 farmers. 

- Piloting 1 pipe based household water and irrigation system for homestead vegetable cultivation for 100 farmers of one hamlet. 

- Procure improvised farming tools (Ex: nap-sac sprayer, hand hoe) to cover all 1,500 farmers in the first year. 

- Conduct season based training on improved High value vegetables (tomato, chili, eggplants and creepers) cultivation techniques with all 1,500 farmers.</narrative>
  </description>
  <description type="1">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">The project &#x201C;Women farmers in vegetable value chain&#x201D; will be implemented with 1,500 smallholder women farmers spread over 30 villages (84 hamlets) over 5 Gram Panchayats of Banka and Katoria Block of Banka District of Bihar. 

The project will focus on optimizing their role and participation in the local agriculture value chain with regard to high value vegetables. The major approach of this project will be to improve the income of these small holder farmers by increasing production of high value vegetables through diversified vegetable farming and improving their access to local and regional markets. The market access will enable the women farmers procure production inputs and sell produce through a collectivized system led by the women farmers themselves. The value chain approach will focus on promoting &amp;amp; strengthening &#x2018;vertical&#x2019; relationships between buyers and suppliers and promoting movement from the vegetable producer to consumer in an effectively established supply chain system.</narrative>
  </description>
